# {{ .prefix }}-writing-plans

<!-- awf:section positioning -->
Writes a plan to `{{ .layout.plansDir }}/YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>.md` per the {{ .prefix }} plan convention. The plan is the execution record; the design lives in the linked ADR(s) (when any exist) — a plan may link zero or more. Do not duplicate rationale — link.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section when-to-invoke -->
## When to invoke

Per `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}`: complex ADR-driven work (multi-commit implementation) and complex non-ADR work where the implementation steps benefit from upfront enumeration — multi-commit work, interdependent steps, refactors applying an already-decided pattern across many sites, or work destined for subagent dispatch. Skip for one-line bugfixes and changes that follow established patterns. When in doubt, write the plan.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Conventions enforced

<!-- awf:section conventions-path -->
- **Path:** `{{ .layout.plansDir }}/YYYY-MM-DD-<kebab-topic>.md`. The date is today (ISO-8601).
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section conventions-header -->
- **Required header:** goal, architecture summary, tech stack (language version, key packages touched), file structure (created / modified / deleted).
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section conventions-tasks -->
- **Tasks:** bite-sized (~2-5 min each), checkbox syntax (`- [ ]`), grouped into phases. Each task specifies exact file paths, the exact content for new files or exact diff for modifications, the exact commands with expected output, and a commit step at the end of each phase. The plan must be executable by an agent with no prior conversation context.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section conventions-no-placeholders -->
- **No placeholders:** no "TBD", "implement later", or "similar to task N". If a step changes a file, the step shows the change verbatim. If a verify step runs a command, the expected output is exact.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section gate-tier-note -->
- **Gate cost:** `{{ .vars.gateCmd }}` (~{{ .vars.gateDuration }}) runs before every commit. Batch closely-related same-shape changes that share one rationale into a single commit; keep genuinely independent concerns separate. A docs-only commit still runs the gate — it just passes quickly with no code to test. See `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}`.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section conventions-test-first -->
- **Test-first for bugs:** add a failing test as its own task before the fix task.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

<!-- awf:section procedure-confirm-scope -->
1. **Confirm scope with the user** if the brainstorm did not already pin down the file structure and phase shape. Resolve any open questions before writing the plan.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section plan-template-ref -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-write-plan -->
2. **Write the plan file in one go** using `Write`. Do not commit yet. The plan must be self-contained — every step executable by an agent with no prior conversation context.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section doc-currency-check -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section self-review -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section plan-commit-step -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section terminal-step -->
3. **Terminal step: invoke `{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-plan`** via the `Skill` tool, passing the plan path. The reviewer applies its lenses and reports findings; route them per the reviewing skill's procedure. After review findings are resolved, commit the plan: `docs(plans): add YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>`.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section plan-lifecycle -->
- Plans are mutable while the corresponding ADR is `Proposed` (or while non-ADR implementation is in flight); they freeze when the ADR flips to `Accepted`/`Implemented` or when a `# Implementation complete (YYYY-MM-DD)` line is added at the top for non-ADR work.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section plan-resync -->
- If planning surfaces a new load-bearing (ADR-worthy) decision, pause: invoke `{{ .prefix }}-proposing-adr` (or amend a still-`Proposed` ADR via `{{ .prefix }}-adr-lifecycle`), let it settle, then resume the plan. The plan↔ADR resync (`{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-plan-resync`) reconciles any resulting drift before implementation.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section notes -->
- The plan is the execution record. The design lives in the linked ADR(s). Do not duplicate design rationale in the plan — link to the ADR(s) instead.
- Plans stay in the repo permanently after freezing. They are the historical record of how a complex change rolled out.
<!-- awf:end -->
